<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7FEE2FEA0AE56" blockId="246.[140,1108,309,651]" box="[140,358,309,333]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E6A7FEE2FEA0AE56" bold="true" box="[140,358,309,333]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
60.8. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E6E2FEE2FEA0AE56" authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1954" box="[201,358,309,333]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hypenodinae">Hypenodinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7FE80FCC2AD5F" blockId="246.[140,1108,309,651]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
Very small (
<quantity id="4CE3EEA59FDAA4D0E73EFE80FE51AE6A" box="[277,407,343,369]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="10.0">10–14 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with relatively narrow wings, clothed with very fine scales. Th e subfamily is defined by several larval characters and by the evenly scaled frons (
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E709FE4AFDB5AEA3" author="Fibiger M &amp; Lafontaine JD" box="[290,627,413,440]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="7 - 690" refId="ref244973" refString="Fibiger M, Lafontaine JD (2005) A review of the higher classification of the Noctuidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to the holarctic fauna. Esperiana 11: 7 - 690." type="journal article" year="2005">Fibiger and Lafontaine 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Interestingly, the recently described 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E203FE4AFE7CAEC0" authority="Fibiger, 2005" authorityName="Fibiger" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Micronoctuidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Micronoctuidae Fibiger, 2005</taxonomicName>
(primarily a palaeotropical group not known from the New World), appears to be very closely related to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E4E3FE34FCA2AEE6" authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1954" box="[712,868,483,509]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hypenodinae">Hypenodinae</taxonomicName>
, based on molecular data (Zahiri et al. in press). Th e 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E42BFDD0FD5FAD3A" authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1954" box="[512,665,519,545]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hypenodinae">Hypenodinae</taxonomicName>
contains the smallest North American noctuids. Th e larvae feed on fungi, lichens and/or algae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E692FD9AFB92AD90" blockId="246.[140,1108,309,651]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
This is a small subfamily, currently with only five North American genera. Two species in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E740FDA7FE1BAD91" box="[363,477,624,650]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypenodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E740FDA7FE1BAD91" box="[363,477,624,650]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">Hypenodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur in AB. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E45DFDA7FD2EAD91" box="[630,744,624,650]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypenodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E45DFDA7FD2EAD91" box="[630,744,624,650]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">Hypenodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was revised by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E5BAFDA6FB96AD90" author="Ferguson DC" box="[913,1104,624,651]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="289 - 298" refId="ref243598" refString="Ferguson DC (1954) A revision of the genus Hypenodes Doubleday with descriptions of new species (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae). Th e Canadian Entomologist 86: 289 - 298." type="journal article" year="1954">Ferguson (1954)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
