<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7FC05FE98ACF1" blockId="246.[140,1108,978,1320]" box="[140,350,978,1002]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E6A7FC05FE98ACF1" bold="true" box="[140,350,978,1002]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
60.9. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E6E2FC05FE98ACF1" box="[201,350,978,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Boletobiinae">Boletobiinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7FC24FD7BAB6C" blockId="246.[140,1108,978,1320]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
Small (
<quantity id="4CE3EEA59FDAA4D0E6F0FC24FE9DAB15" box="[219,347,1011,1038]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="23.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="22.0">22–25 mm</quantity>
wingspan), broad-winged nocturnal moths, superficially very similar to some geometrids. They are defined by a number of adult and larval characters, including the long, thin, roughly scaled palps and the fully scaled frons of the adults. Th e larvae feed on mushrooms and bracket fungi.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E692FB57FC12AA33" blockId="246.[140,1108,978,1320]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E6C0FB57FEBCAB81" box="[235,378,1152,1178]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Boletobiinae">Boletobiinae</taxonomicName>
occur in both North America and Eurasia, with about 18 species in four genera in North America, including one introduced European genus (
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E5D0FB73FF6CABFB" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Parascotia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E5D0FB73FF6CABFB" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">Parascotia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and one that is likely misplaced in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E4A8FB10FCD4ABFA" box="[643,786,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Boletobiinae">Boletobiinae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E50FFB10FC50ABFB" authorityName="Grote" authorityYear="1883" box="[804,918,1223,1248]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Prosoparia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E50FFB10FC50ABFB" box="[804,918,1223,1248]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">Prosoparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; Lafontaine and Schmidt in press). One species is found in AB. Some North American species, including the sole species occurring in AB, were covered by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E4CCFADAFC16AA33" author="Franclemont JG" box="[743,976,1293,1320]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="826 - 833" refId="ref245745" refString="Franclemont JG (1985) A new species of Parascotia with notes on the genera Mycterophora and Parascotia (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: incertae sedis). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 87: 826 - 833." type="journal article" year="1985">Franclemont (1985)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7FA80FD63AA8B" blockId="246.[140,1094,1366,1459]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
1683 R 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E708FA80FCA7AA76" authority="(Walker, [1863]) E Jul" authorityName="E Jul" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[291,865,1366,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mycterophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inexplicata">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E708FA80FDC4AA77" box="[291,514,1367,1388]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">Mycterophora inexplicata</emphasis>
(Walker, [1863]) E Jul
</taxonomicName>
– L Jul – B g T: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E770FAADFE26AA8B" author="Forbes WTM" box="[347,480,1402,1424]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref245268" refString="Forbes WTM (1954) Th e Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states, Part III. Noctuidae. Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station Memoirs 329: 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1954">Forbes (1954)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E7C2FAADFD63AA8B" author="Franclemont JG" box="[489,677,1402,1424]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="826 - 833" refId="ref245745" refString="Franclemont JG (1985) A new species of Parascotia with notes on the genera Mycterophora and Parascotia (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: incertae sedis). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 87: 826 - 833." type="journal article" year="1985">Franclemont (1985)</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E76AFA49FD25AAA8" blockId="246.[140,1094,1366,1459]" box="[321,739,1437,1459]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
L: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E770FA49FE35AAA8" author="Bowman K" box="[347,499,1437,1459]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="121 - 165" refId="ref237866" refString="Bowman K (1951) An annotated list of the Lepidoptera of Alberta. Canadian Journal of Zoology 29: 121 - 165." type="journal article" year="1951">Bowman (1951)</bibRefCitation>
C: CNC, NFRC, UASM
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7FA35FE42AAE1" blockId="246.[140,1108,1506,1672]" box="[140,388,1506,1530]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDAA4D0E6A7FA35FE42AAE1" bold="true" box="[140,388,1506,1530]" italics="true" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
60.10. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E6FCFA35FE42AAE1" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1913" box="[215,388,1506,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phytometrinae">Phytometrinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDAA4D0E6A7F9D3FC46A993" blockId="246.[140,1108,1506,1672]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247">
A small group of small to medium-sized (
<quantity id="4CE3EEA59FDAA4D0E44AF9D3FD24A905" box="[609,738,1540,1566]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="20.0">20–30 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with relatively broad wings. Th e group is defined by a number of derived character states, mainly genitalic. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E706F99DFE12A97F" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1913" box="[301,468,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phytometrinae">Phytometrinae</taxonomicName>
have traditionally been included within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDAA4D0E5FBF99DFB89A97F" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1851" box="[976,1103,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hypeninae">Hypeninae</taxonomicName>
, but the subfamily was reinstated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDAA4D0E409F9BAFCBBA993" author="Fibiger M &amp; Lafontaine JD" box="[546,893,1645,1672]" pageId="246" pageNumber="247" pagination="7 - 690" refId="ref244973" refString="Fibiger M, Lafontaine JD (2005) A review of the higher classification of the Noctuidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to the holarctic fauna. Esperiana 11: 7 - 690." type="journal article" year="2005">Fibiger and Lafontaine (2005)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDBA4D1E692FF70FE71AE1C" blockId="247.[140,1107,166,264]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
In North America, the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E41EFF70FD1AAFDA" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1913" box="[565,732,167,193]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phytometrinae">Phytometrinae</taxonomicName>
contains some 25 species in nine genera. The group is in need of revision. Th e lone AB species was treated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E222FF1DFF1FAE13" author="Forbes WTM" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref245268" refString="Forbes WTM (1954) Th e Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states, Part III. Noctuidae. Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station Memoirs 329: 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1954">Forbes (1954)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E739FF3AFE72AE1C" author="Covell CV Jr" box="[274,436,237,263]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref240257" refString="Covell CV Jr (1984) A field guide to moths of eastern North America. Houghton Mifflin, Boston, MA, Peterson Field Guide Series No. 30, 496 pp." type="book" year="1984">Covell (1984)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDBA4D1E6A7FEE0FDADAE6B" blockId="247.[140,1094,311,403]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
1684 R 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E708FEE0FCA9AE57" authority="Grote, 1873 M Jun" authorityName="Grote" authorityYear="1873" box="[291,879,311,333]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Spargaloma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexpunctata">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E708FEE0FE31AE56" box="[291,503,311,333]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Spargaloma sexpunctata</emphasis>
Grote, 1873 M Jun
</taxonomicName>
– M Jul – B g T: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E770FE8DFE26AE6B" author="Forbes WTM" box="[347,480,346,368]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 433" refId="ref245268" refString="Forbes WTM (1954) Th e Lepidoptera of New York and neighboring states, Part III. Noctuidae. Cornell University Agricultural Experiment Station Memoirs 329: 1 - 433." type="journal article" year="1954">Forbes (1954)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E7C2FE8DFDADAE6B" author="Covell CV Jr" box="[489,619,346,368]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref240257" refString="Covell CV Jr (1984) A field guide to moths of eastern North America. Houghton Mifflin, Boston, MA, Peterson Field Guide Series No. 30, 496 pp." type="book" year="1984">Covell (1984)</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDBA4D1E76AFEA9FD25AE88" blockId="247.[140,1094,311,403]" box="[321,739,381,403]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
L: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E770FEA9FE35AE88" author="Bowman K" box="[347,499,381,403]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="121 - 165" refId="ref237866" refString="Bowman K (1951) An annotated list of the Lepidoptera of Alberta. Canadian Journal of Zoology 29: 121 - 165." type="journal article" year="1951">Bowman (1951)</bibRefCitation>
C: CNC, NFRC, UASM
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDBA4D1E6A7FE15FEF8AEC1" blockId="247.[140,1108,450,932]" box="[140,318,450,474]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E6A7FE15FEF8AEC1" bold="true" box="[140,318,450,474]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
60.11. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E6FCFE15FEF8AEC1" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[215,318,450,474]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Erebinae">Erebinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDBA4D1E6A7FE34FD6FADB5" blockId="247.[140,1108,450,932]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
Medium-sized to very large (
<quantity id="4CE3EEA59FDBA4D1E7E5FE34FD9BAEE5" box="[462,605,483,510]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" unit="mm" value="105.0" valueMax="160.0" valueMin="50.0">50–160 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths, often with brightly color- ed hindwings or with eyespots on fore- and hingwings (
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E524FDD0FC5BAD39" authorityName="Guenée" authorityYear="1852" box="[783,925,519,546]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Thermesiini">Thermesiini</taxonomicName>
). Th e subfamily contains many large colorful species, as well as several species that are active during the day. Larval hostplants are a diverse array of vascular plants, but tend to be specialized within groups, such as deciduous trees and shrubs for the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E53BFDA7FC4EAD91" authorityName="Boisduval" authorityYear="1828" box="[784,904,624,650]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Catocalini">Catocalini</taxonomicName>
; a few (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E23AFDA6FF12ADB6" authorityName="McDunnough" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Caenurgina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E23AFDA6FF12ADB6" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Caenurgina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.) are occasional pests of forage crops.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30110CB9FDBA4D1E692FD60FB95ACBF" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BA443409FDBA4D1E692FD60FB95ACBF" blockId="247.[140,1108,450,932]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E692FD60FEDAADCA" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[185,284,695,721]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Erebinae">Erebinae</taxonomicName>
occur worldwide but are most diverse and abundant in tropical and subtropical regions. Th ere are approximately 325 species in 65 genera in North America, of which 35 species are reported from AB. Th e group as a whole is in need of work, but revisions have been published for the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E49FFCF7FC37AC21" authority="(Richards 1939)" baseAuthorityName="Richards" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[692,1009,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Melipotini">
Melipotini (
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E515FCF7FC2FAC21" author="Richards AG Jr" box="[830,1001,800,826]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 100" refId="ref264004" refString="Richards AG Jr (1939) A revision of the North American species of the Phoberia - Melipotis - Drasteria group of moths (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae). Entomologica Americana 19: 1 - 100." type="journal article" year="1939">Richards 1939</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and the genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E6F0FC94FDD9AC45" authority="(Franclemont 1957)" baseAuthorityName="Franclemont" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[219,543,835,862]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Euclidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E6F0FC94FEF0AC46" box="[219,310,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Euclidia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E768FC94FDD1AC45" author="Franclemont JG" box="[323,535,835,862]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="5 - 15" refId="ref245532" refString="Franclemont JG (1957) The genus Euclidia, with the description of a new species (Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: Catocalinae). Bulletin of the Brooklyn Entomological Society 52: 5 - 15." type="journal article" year="1957">Franclemont 1957</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E47EFC94FCE1AC45" authority="(Smith 1908)" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[597,807,835,862]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Zale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E47EFC94FD43AC46" box="[597,645,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Zale</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E4B8FC94FCD8AC45" author="Smith JB" box="[659,798,835,862]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="209 - 275" refId="ref267119" refString="Smith JB (1908) A revision of some species of Noctuidae heretofore referred to the genus Homoptera Boidsduval. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 35 (1645): 209 - 275." type="journal article" year="1908">Smith 1908</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FDBA4D1E58CFC94FBC0AC46" authorityName="Schrank" authorityYear="1802" box="[935,1030,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Catocala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E58CFC94FBC0AC46" box="[935,1030,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Catocala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FDBA4D1E73CFCB0FD67AC9A" author="Barnes W &amp; McDunnough JH" box="[279,673,871,897]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref236525" refString="Barnes W, McDunnough JH (1918 a) Illustrations of the North American species of the genus Catocala. Memoirs of the American Museum of Natural History, New Series 3, 47 pp." type="book" year="1918">Barnes and McDunnough (1918a)</bibRefCitation>
; a modern revision of the genus is currently under way as an upcoming 
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FDBA4D1E427FC5DFCD5ACBF" box="[524,787,906,932]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Moths of North America</emphasis>
fascicle by Gall and Hawks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
